a) Multi-Language Setup (i18n.ts & LanguageSwitcher.tsx)

IGNORE_WHEN_COPYING_START

    // src/lib/i18n.ts
import i18n from 'i18next';
import { initReactI18next } from 'react-i18next';
import LanguageDetector from 'i18next-browser-languagedetector';
import en from '../locales/en.json';
import ar from '../locales/ar.json';
import ku from '../locales/ku.json';

i18n
  .use(LanguageDetector)
  .use(initReactI18next)
  .init({
    resources: {
      en: { translation: en },
      ar: { translation: ar },
      ku: { translation: ku },
    },
    fallbackLng: 'en',
    interpolation: {
      escapeValue: false,
    },
    detection: {
      order: ['localStorage', 'navigator'],
      caches: ['localStorage'],
    },
  });

export default i18n;

// src/components/ui/LanguageSwitcher.tsx
import React from 'react';
import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next';
import { USFlag, IraqFlag, KurdistanFlag } from '../icons/FlagIcons'; // Assume these exist

const languages = [
  { code: 'en', name: 'English', Flag: USFlag },
  { code: 'ar', name: 'العربية', Flag: IraqFlag },
  { code: 'ku', name: 'کوردی', Flag: KurdistanFlag },
];

export const LanguageSwitcher: React.FC = () => {
  const { i18n } = useTranslation();

  const changeLanguage = (lng: string) => {
    i18n.changeLanguage(lng);
  };

  return (
    <div className="flex items-center space-x-2">
      {languages.map(({ code, Flag }) => (
        <button
          key={code}
          onClick={() => changeLanguage(code)}
          className={`p-1 rounded-full transition-transform duration-200 ${
            i18n.language === code ? 'ring-2 ring-teal-400 scale-110' : 'opacity-70 hover:opacity-100'
          }`}
        >
          <Flag className="w-8 h-8 rounded-full" />
        </button>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

import React from 'react';
import { MapContainer, TileLayer, Marker, Popup } from 'react-leaflet';
import MarkerClusterGroup from 'react-leaflet-cluster';
import 'leaflet/dist/leaflet.css';
import 'react-leaflet-cluster/lib/styles.scss';
// You'll need to configure Leaflet's default icon
// import L from 'leaflet';
// delete L.Icon.Default.prototype._getIconUrl;

// Assume useMapEvents is a custom hook fetching geo-data
// const { events, loading } = useMapEvents();

interface EventGeoData {
  id: string;
  position: [number, number]; // [lat, lng]
  title: string;
  date: string;
}

const InteractiveMap: React.FC<{ events: EventGeoData[] }> = ({ events }) => {
  return (
    <MapContainer center={[36.19, 44.00]} zoom={10} style={{ height: '100%', width: '100%' }}>
      <TileLayer
        url="https://{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png"
        attribution='&copy; <a href="https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright">OpenStreetMap</a> contributors'
      />

          <Marker key={event.id} position={event.position}>

              <a href={`/events/${event.id}`}>See Details</a>
            </Popup>
          </Marker>
        ))}
      </MarkerClusterGroup>
    </MapContainer>
  );
};

c) "Top Events" Dot-Based Navigation (TopEventsCarousel.tsx)

This component uses framer-motion for the smooth, interactive animation.

code TypeScript
IGNORE_WHEN_COPYING_START
IGNORE_WHEN_COPYING_END
    // src/components/home/TopEventsCarousel.tsx
import React, from 'react';
import { useState } from 'react';
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'framer-motion';

// Assume events are passed as a prop
const TopEventsCarousel: React.FC<{ events: any[] }> = ({ events }) => {
  const [selectedIndex, setSelectedIndex] = useState(0);
  const selectedEvent = events[selectedIndex];

  return (
    <div className="w-full flex flex-col items-center py-8">
      {/* Event Details Display */}
      <AnimatePresence mode="wait">
        <motion.div
          key={selectedIndex}
          initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
          animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
          exit={{ opacity: 0, y: -20 }}
          transition={{ duration: 0.3 }}
          className="text-center mb-8"
        >
          <img src={selectedEvent.imageUrl} className="w-48 h-32 object-cover rounded-lg mx-auto mb-4" />
          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold">{selectedEvent.title}</h3>
          <p className="text-gray-400">{selectedEvent.date}</p>
          <button className="mt-2 px-4 py-2 bg-teal-500 rounded-full">See Details</button>
        </motion.div>
      </AnimatePresence>

      {/* Dot Navigator */}
      <div className="w-full h-px bg-gray-700 relative flex justify-center items-center">
        <div className="flex items-center" style={{ columnGap: '60px' }}>
          {events.map((event, index) => (
            <button
              key={event.id}
              onClick={() => setSelectedIndex(index)}
              className="relative"
            >
              <motion.div
                className="w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-gray-500"
                animate={{ scale: selectedIndex === index ? 1.5 : 1 }}
              />
              {selectedIndex === index && (
                <motion.div
                  layoutId="selected-dot-highlight"
                  className="absolute -top-1 -left-1 w-5 h-5 rounded-full bg-teal-500/50"
                  style={{ borderRadius: '50%' }}
                  transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 500, damping: 30 }}
                />
              )}
            </button>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

5. API Endpoint Definitions

These are the core RESTful endpoints the backend should expose.

  • Authentication

    • POST /api/auth/register - Creates a new user.

    • POST /api/auth/login - Authenticates a user and returns a JWT.

    • GET /api/auth/me - (Protected) Returns the current user's profile.

  • Events

    • POST /api/events - (Protected) Creates a new event.

    • GET /api/events - Fetches a paginated list of events with filters (?city=...&category=...).

    • GET /api/events/map - Fetches events optimized for the map (ID, title, coordinates).

    • GET /api/events/:id - Fetches details for a single event.

    • PUT /api/events/:id - (Protected, Owner only) Updates an event.

    • DELETE /api/events/:id - (Protected, Owner only) Deletes an event.

  • AI

    • GET /api/ai/recommendations - (Protected) Returns a list of personalized event recommendations for the current user.

    • POST /api/ai/search - Takes a natural language query and returns structured search results.

6. AI Implementation Plan

This is a phased approach, starting with data collection and moving to more complex models.

  • Phase 1: Foundational Data Collection (Months 1-2)

    • Goal: Start collecting user interaction data.

    • Action: Implement the user_event_interactions table and create a backend endpoint that logs every significant user action (viewing an event page, saving an event, sharing an event). This data is crucial for all future AI work.

  • Phase 2: "Smart Search" with NLP (Months 3-4)

    • Goal: Allow users to search with natural language.

    • Action:

      1. Create a Python AI microservice using FastAPI.

      2. Integrate a lightweight NLP library like spaCy.

      3. Train a custom Named Entity Recognition (NER) model to identify CITY, CATEGORY, and DATE entities from user queries (e.g., "tech events in erbil this weekend").

      4. The /api/ai/search endpoint will process the query, extract entities, and translate them into structured filters to query the main events API.

  • Phase 3: Personalized Recommendations (Months 5-6)

    • Goal: Provide a "For You" section with personalized event recommendations.

    • Action:

      1. In the Python service, use the collected interaction data.

      2. Implement a Collaborative Filtering model. A simple approach is using matrix factorization (e.g., with the surprise library) to find users with similar tastes and recommend events they liked.

      3. Schedule a daily or weekly job to retrain the model with new interaction data.

      4. The GET /api/ai/recommendations endpoint will query this model to get a list of event IDs for the logged-in user.
